<h1>Getting Started!</h1>
<article>
    <h2>Composer</h2>
    <p>Composer is a Dependency management tool for PHP. You can use it to easily install and keep track of 'packages',
        like Laravel. To install composer, first visit <a rel="external" target="_blank"
            href="https://getcomposer.org/download/">Download Composer</a> and install the program on your computer.
        Either use the windows installer from <a rel="external" target="_blank"
            href="https://getcomposer.org/Composer-Setup.exe">here</a> or install it manually.
    </p>
</article>
<article>
    <h2>Installing laravel with Composer</h2>
    <p>
        We can now use Composer to automatically install laravel for us. Open a console panel and go the the directory
        where you wish to install Laravel. This can be done using the
        <span class="code-block">cd</span> command. Then execute these commands for creating your first Laravel project:
    </p>
    <p class="code-block">
        composer create-project laravel/laravel [project name]<br> cd [project name]
    </p>
    <p>
        Now that your project has been created, you can use the
        <span class="code-block text-code-expression">serve</span> command to start Laravel's local development server.
    </p>
    <p class="code-block">
        php artisan serve
    </p>
    <p class="text-larger text-center">
        Further information can be found at Laravel's own installation page:<br>
        <a class="text-bold" rel="external" target="_blank" href="https://laravel.com/docs/8.x/installation">Laravel
            Installation</a>
    </p>
</article>
